│                                                                               │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                               │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                   │
│ The verifier crash indicates a dominance violation: an insertelement          │
│ instruction creating a <4 x ptr> vector from the scalar pointer %0 does not   │
│ dominate a subsequent shufflevector that uses it. This typically happens when │
│ the pass emits a use (shuffle) before the definition (insert) in the IR order │
│ or across basic blocks, violating SSA dominance. Given the minimized          │
│ reproducer and the log, the first transformation leading to the broken IR is  │
│ in SLP vectorizer's gather routine and its shuffle emission.                  │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ The opt log shows the verifier failing on a vector of pointers:               │
│   %6 = insertelement <4 x ptr> poison, ptr %0, i32 0                          │
│   %4 = shufflevector <4 x ptr> %6, <4 x ptr> poison, <4 x i32>                │
│ zeroinitializer                                                               │
│ The mask is zeroinitializer, meaning a broadcast or identity permutation. The │
│ SLP vectorizer often constructs a vector using insertelement(s) and then      │
│ emits a shufflevector to broadcast/permute. The log suggests the              │
│ shufflevector was emitted before all required insertelements were inserted in │
│ a position dominating the shuffle. The first transformation point is the      │
│ verifier, but the IR was broken earlier by SLP.                               │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ In BoUpSLP::gather (lines ~14180-14430), the algorithm builds a vector Vec by │
│ inserting constants first, then potentially combines with a Root shuffle      │
│ early, and only afterwards inserts non-constants and postponed instructions.  │
│ Specifically, the sequence:                                                   │
│ - Build Vec starting from poison.                                             │
│ - Insert constant lanes first.                                                │
│ - If Root exists:                                                             │
│   - If Vec is still poison (i.e., no constants were inserted yet), it sets    │
│ Vec = OriginalRoot; else it emits Vec = CreateShuffle(Root, Vec, Mask).       │
│ - Then it proceeds to insert non-constant values and postponed instructions.  │
│ This means the shuffle combining Root and Vec may be emitted before the       │
│ insertelement instructions for non-constant lanes, or, if Vec is poison, the  │
│ code sets Vec to OriginalRoot, effectively using the existing shuffle before  │
│ any insertelement. Later insertelelements then may be placed after, not       │
│ dominating that shuffle use, especially in loops/preheaders where insertion   │
│ points differ.                                                                │
│                                                                               │
│ The dominance error in the reproducer aligns with this: a broadcast           │
│ shufflevector (zeroinitializer mask) is emitted using a vector built from an  │
│ insertelement that appears later, violating dominance.                        │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                    │
│ Edit file llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp lines 14306-14322   │
│ to delay the Root combination until after all insertelements (both constants  │
│ and non-constants, including postponed ones) are emitted. Concretely:         │
│ - Remove/disable the early handling:                                          │
│   if (Root) {                                                                 │
│     if (isa<PoisonValue>(Vec)) {                                              │
│       Vec = OriginalRoot;                                                     │
│     } else {                                                                  │
│       Vec = CreateShuffle(Root, Vec, Mask);                                   │
│       ...                                                                     │
│     }                                                                         │
│   }                                                                           │
│ - Instead, store Root/OriginalRoot/Mask and perform the CreateShuffle         │
│ combination only after all CreateInsertElement calls for NonConsts and        │
│ PostponedInsts are completed. This ensures the vector built from              │
│ insertelement(s) dominates the shuffle use.                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ This change preserves correctness and removes the possibility of emitting a   │
│ shuffle before its operand definitions dominate it.                           │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ By deferring the combination with Root until after all insertelement          │
│ emissions, we guarantee SSA dominance: definitions of vectors via             │
│ insertelement dominate any shufflevector that uses them. This addresses the   │
│ verifier crash reported. The expected effect is that the SLP vectorizer will  │
│ still construct the intended vector and permutation but in a correct IR       │
│ order, eliminating the "Instruction does not dominate all uses" error.        │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                               │
